>>54044555
Hard sci-fi is pretty difficult to pull off, both due to the sheer amount of research you need to do and how much work it's going to be justifying the existence of anthros in a believable manner. Somewhere in between where you have soft elements like "scientific" anthros and story elements while still for the most part abiding to actual science and physics is probably the hardest sci-fi that's going to work for a /hmofa/ story.

Since it's topical think of the softer sci-fi setting of the Avatar movies, where you have both fairly realistic technology that abides by real physics (aircraft designs, interstellar spacecraft) but also a lot of handwavy material (Avatars, most of Pandora as a whole) that plays more fast and loose with actual science. I tend to find that internally justifying it within the story using generally good science is about as far as you really need to go, most readers are able to suspend their disbelief when it comes to the nitty gritty details of how precisely everything works.

Anonymous Sat 28 Jan 2023 23:43:23 No.54045661 Report

>>54044555
I find hard sf to be a bit of a paradox. The strength of science fiction is positing what ifs based on things that aren't real, at least in my opinion. That can be rather high brow, like say representing your loss of faith in society by presenting a purposefully broken setting that falls apart the harder the main character looks at it, or by imagining how cool warfare would be if it was fought exclusively through giant robots. Hard sf has some leeway, but it purposefully limits itself by setting these boundaries while also setting itself a goal of having the science be a main component in its setting and story. And frankly, the hard science fiction I've read has been fairly boring. But on the other hand, I do understand the merit of keeping the science part of the fiction grounded, and I do enjoy the feel of more realistic sf.

Ah, but it was an inherently political, inherently didactic genre created by four Canadians and one American acidhead as a reaction to their belief that Ronald Reagan was going to start a nuclear war. It is rooted in the Cold War, and in this Canadian funhouse-mirror view of American politics and American capitalism. Strangely, outside the English-speaking world, one of the stereotypes about Americans is that Americans say "I'll sue you." Cyberpunk settings are always lawless superultrahypermegalocapitalism. There is no law and no lawyers, and people who complain too loudly about Bigbizco's polluting factory get disappeared in the middle of the night by a plausibly deniable (not really) Bigbizco death squad. Because cyberpunk isn't about body modification, or getting an Ethernet socket surgically implanted in your forehead with wires going directly into your brain. It's about inhuman destructive capitalism and jingoistic American politicians bullying the poor misunderstood Russians until they blow up the world, unless acid rain kills us all in the meantime. http://lib.ru/STERLINGB/interzone.txt Bruce Sterling, one of the genre's creators, went on at great length about what the genre he created is and isn't, what it does and doesn't mean, what does and doesn't qualify.

I think that's a bit of reductionist idea of a genre and a movement. They don't really work like that, though of course we have to acknowledge the creators' words especially because the origins often have that specific historical context. Some purists will argue that is that and be done with it, but like all things in literature, you can't put that cat back in the bag after you put it out in the world. I say this as someone unfortunate enough to be a semi-professional in the realm of literature.

I don't think you can really argue that the questions have really changed that much, but it has been commercialized which the most sad but ironic part of it. Still, I mean I could make a big list but have we really seen the last of late stage capitalism woes? Are creeping corporate powers really gone? Are we not literally still at a very low boil of a nuclear threat with Russia and are climate threats somehow magically gone?

I think cyberpunk as a concept is more relevant than ever, but I can't say the original spirit is still there. Nonetheless, meaning and genre shifts just like the world turns regardless of how many people it drags kicking and screaming with it.

That said, they don't write it like Phillip K. Dick did anymore for sure.
